301
00:13:13.668 --> 00:13:17.047
♪ Roam if you want to ♪

302
00:13:17.130 --> 00:13:20.634
♪ Roam around the world ♪

303
00:13:20.717 --> 00:13:24.471
♪ Roam if you want to ♪

304
00:13:24.554 --> 00:13:27.682
♪ Without wings. without wheels ♪

305
00:13:27.766 --> 00:13:30.519
♪ Roam if you want to ♪

306
00:13:31.937 --> 00:13:34.022
♪ Roam around the world...

307
00:13:34.105 --> 00:13:35.232
Bruiser?

308
00:13:35.315 --> 00:13:36.608
Wish me luck.

309
00:13:36.691 --> 00:13:37.817
[barking]

310
00:13:37.901 --> 00:13:39.319
[sighs]

311
00:13:39.402 --> 00:13:42.781
♪ Without anything but the love we feel ♪♪

312
00:13:44.324 --> 00:13:46.743
-[Eva] Do you have your beeper?
-Yes.

313
00:13:46.826 --> 00:13:48.828
-Lunch money?
-Yes.

314
00:13:49.579 --> 00:13:50.705
Your armor?

315
00:13:50.789 --> 00:13:52.123
My what?

316
00:13:54.251 --> 00:13:55.418
It is my armor.

317
00:13:55.502 --> 00:13:57.045
I know.

318
00:13:58.255 --> 00:14:00.215
-Whoa!
-[gasps]

319
00:14:00.298 --> 00:14:01.466
-[all oohing]
-[Eva] Oh. my God!

320
00:14:04.803 --> 00:14:06.263
Oh.

321
00:14:09.516 --> 00:14:10.976
Where are the manners?

322
00:14:11.059 --> 00:14:12.519
[scoffs]

323
00:14:13.520 --> 00:14:15.855
Boo! Boo. Boo.

324
00:14:20.610 --> 00:14:21.945
Hey.

325
00:14:22.445 --> 00:14:24.072
It's gonna be fine.

326
00:14:25.448 --> 00:14:27.492
Feeling very blond.

327
00:14:29.578 --> 00:14:30.787
There's another one.

328
00:14:30.870 --> 00:14:31.913
[Elle gasps]

329
00:14:31.997 --> 00:14:33.957
-Mom. her roots.
-I know.

330
00:14:34.040 --> 00:14:35.792
Yeah. I hope that's a choice.

331
00:14:38.461 --> 00:14:40.547
-[car door opens]
-Hey.

332
00:14:41.798 --> 00:14:42.924
You got this.

333
00:14:43.008 --> 00:14:45.010
[indistinct chatter]

334
00:14:49.639 --> 00:14:51.266
-[car door closes]
-[♪ L7 plays "Shove"]

335
00:14:52.726 --> 00:14:54.144
[sighs]

336
00:15:04.404 --> 00:15:06.865
♪ Get out of my way ♪

337
00:15:06.948 --> 00:15:08.241
-♪ or I might shove...
-Nice umbrella.

338
00:15:08.325 --> 00:15:09.743
Thanks. It's an heirloom.

339
00:15:09.826 --> 00:15:11.786
[girl] She's joking.
You look like an idiot.

340
00:15:11.870 --> 00:15:13.997
♪ or I'm gonna shove ♪

341
00:15:14.080 --> 00:15:16.291
♪ Landlord doesn't like my dog ♪

342
00:15:17.709 --> 00:15:20.879
-♪ Shove ♪
-♪ My eyes are burning from the smog ♪

343
00:15:20.962 --> 00:15:22.380
-[Elle] Hi.
-Ew.

344
00:15:22.464 --> 00:15:23.965
-♪ Shove ♪
-♪ My neighbors ♪

345
00:15:24.049 --> 00:15:26.343
♪ say I jam too loud...

346
00:15:26.426 --> 00:15:28.553
Ooh. Chess.

347
00:15:28.637 --> 00:15:30.263
I love smart people.

348
00:15:30.347 --> 00:15:32.098
[girl 2] So you hate yourself.

349
00:15:33.141 --> 00:15:35.101
-♪ Get out of my way ♪
-[school bell ringing]

350
00:15:35.185 --> 00:15:37.979
♪ or I might shove ♪

351
00:15:38.063 --> 00:15:39.939
♪ Get out of my way ♪

352
00:15:40.023 --> 00:15:42.651
♪ or I'm gonna shove ♪♪

353
00:15:42.734 --> 00:15:44.319
It's a total straw man argument.

354
00:15:44.402 --> 00:15:46.863
No one actually thinks that Eddie Vedder

355
00:15:46.946 --> 00:15:50.033
-is better than Kurt Cobain.
-[student] Thank you.

356
00:15:50.116 --> 00:15:51.785
Now if you were to say Chris Cornell...

357
00:15:51.868 --> 00:15:53.953
[student 2] No way. dude.

358
00:15:54.037 --> 00:15:56.915
[overlapping chatter]

359
00:16:09.386 --> 00:16:11.429
Did you do anything fun over the summer?

360
00:16:11.513 --> 00:16:12.764
-[muffled music playing]
-[mouths]

361
00:16:12.847 --> 00:16:13.932
Mm-hmm.

362
00:16:15.016 --> 00:16:16.059
What?

363
00:16:16.142 --> 00:16:18.395
This summer. Did you do anything fun?

364
00:16:18.478 --> 00:16:19.479
What do you mean?

365
00:16:24.567 --> 00:16:26.069
W-What's that?

366
00:16:26.152 --> 00:16:27.445
A zine.

367
00:16:27.529 --> 00:16:29.948
[gasps]
Oh. like. a magazine?

368
00:16:30.031 --> 00:16:34.828
I have two subscriptions to Cosmo.
one for my archives and one I can crease.

369
00:16:34.911 --> 00:16:36.871
No. like. a zine.

370
00:16:38.415 --> 00:16:41.334
Cool. What else are you into?

371
00:16:41.418 --> 00:16:43.211
Did-did someone put you up to this?

372
00:16:43.294 --> 00:16:46.715
I'm Elle. I like iced coffee.
the month of July.

373
00:16:46.798 --> 00:16:50.510
and when people dress kind of tennisy.
even if they don't play tennis.

374
00:16:51.594 --> 00:16:52.637
Was it Kimberly?

375
00:16:52.721 --> 00:16:54.431
[door closes]

376
00:16:54.514 --> 00:16:56.933
Uh. welcome to first period.

377
00:16:57.016 --> 00:16:59.018
I am Mr. Nichols.

378
00:16:59.102 --> 00:17:01.604
and this is...

379
00:17:02.689 --> 00:17:04.941
...English. Okay.

380
00:17:05.024 --> 00:17:07.777
Let's just dive right into it.

381
00:17:07.861 --> 00:17:12.198
Much Ado About Nothing.

382
00:17:12.282 --> 00:17:14.492
It was the shortest thing
on your summer reading list.

383
00:17:14.576 --> 00:17:17.871
so it's kind of a gimme. Ah. yes?

384
00:17:18.955 --> 00:17:20.874
First of all. nice to meet you.

385
00:17:20.957 --> 00:17:24.753
Second of all.
I never received a summer reading list.

386
00:17:24.836 --> 00:17:26.838
It was mailed out in May.

387
00:17:26.921 --> 00:17:29.883
[chuckles] Yeah. I. uh...
I actually didn't know

388
00:17:29.966 --> 00:17:31.384
I'd be going to this school
until kind of recently.

389
00:17:31.468 --> 00:17:34.637
There was this whole thing with my dad.

390
00:17:34.721 --> 00:17:36.473
Don't ask.

391
00:17:36.556 --> 00:17:38.933
Like. seriously don't ask.
I can't talk about it.

392
00:17:39.017 --> 00:17:40.643
[whispering] NDA.

393
00:17:41.811 --> 00:17:43.480
Well. you'll have
to read the play this week.

394
00:17:43.563 --> 00:17:47.108
because you will each be writing a paper
on its themes

395
00:17:47.192 --> 00:17:48.860
-this weekend.
-[students groaning]

396
00:17:48.943 --> 00:17:50.153
Hi.

397
00:17:50.236 --> 00:17:53.239
Hi. At my old school.
we were given the option

398
00:17:53.323 --> 00:17:55.033
to have our own take on the assignment.

399
00:17:55.116 --> 00:17:56.367
Is that an option here?

400
00:17:56.451 --> 00:17:57.952
Uh. your own take?

401
00:17:58.036 --> 00:18:01.831
Yeah. Like. we could create a song
based on the reading or a short film.

402
00:18:01.915 --> 00:18:04.292
I went to middle school
with Tim Burton's nephew.

403
00:18:04.375 --> 00:18:06.169
and you have not experienced
Tuck Everlasting

404
00:18:06.252 --> 00:18:08.171
until you've seen it in stop-motion.

405
00:18:08.254 --> 00:18:09.881
-[scattered chuckles]
-[murmuring]

406
00:18:09.964 --> 00:18:12.675
I'm sure I haven't. but I would say "no."

407
00:18:12.759 --> 00:18:15.053
That's not an option.

408
00:18:15.136 --> 00:18:16.679
A paper is a paper.

409
00:18:18.264 --> 00:18:19.390
Oh.

410
00:18:19.474 --> 00:18:20.767
-[groaning]
-[murmuring]

411
00:18:22.018 --> 00:18:24.771
Just try to keep up. Okay?

412
00:18:26.022 --> 00:18:28.316
So. Much Ado About Nothing.
What is it? It is a play.

413
00:18:28.399 --> 00:18:30.109
And what do we know about it?

414
00:18:30.193 --> 00:18:34.364
It was written by William Shakespeare.
the great bard himself.

415
00:18:34.447 --> 00:18:37.784
We're still accepting donations
for the auction.

416
00:18:37.867 --> 00:18:40.036
Still accepting donations for the auction.

417
00:18:41.037 --> 00:18:42.497
We're still accepting donations
for the auction.

418
00:18:42.580 --> 00:18:44.749
[gasps]
Holy Pierce Brosnan.

419
00:18:44.833 --> 00:18:47.544
-[Dustin] We're accepting donations.
-A kindred spirit.

420
00:18:47.627 --> 00:18:51.339
So nice to meet a fellow stranger
in a strange land.

421
00:18:52.423 --> 00:18:53.925
Did I see you this morning?

422
00:18:55.009 --> 00:18:58.721
You're the guy who almost hit
my mom's car with your skateboard.

423
00:18:58.805 --> 00:19:00.849
I thought you were a jerk.
but you're just British.

424
00:19:00.932 --> 00:19:03.518
You're used to driving
on the wrong side of the road.

425
00:19:03.601 --> 00:19:05.645
which I totally get.

426
00:19:05.728 --> 00:19:08.064
Not the driving thing.
I'm not from here. either.

427
00:19:08.147 --> 00:19:09.524
Wow.

428
00:19:09.607 --> 00:19:11.484
Is this place different. right?

429
00:19:11.568 --> 00:19:12.652
Right.

430
00:19:12.735 --> 00:19:14.946
Have you noticed
how many hoodies they wear?

431
00:19:15.029 --> 00:19:17.115
What is that about?

432
00:19:17.198 --> 00:19:18.908
I'm Elle Woo-- Oh.

433
00:19:18.992 --> 00:19:22.954
Dustin. And I've lived here
for. like. nine years.

434
00:19:23.037 --> 00:19:25.415
so that's most of my life.

435
00:19:25.498 --> 00:19:26.916
Cool.

436
00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:29.252
I'll just go to my locker.

437
00:19:34.799 --> 00:19:37.135
Which is right by yours. Great.

438
00:19:41.347 --> 00:19:42.557
Oh.

439
00:19:42.640 --> 00:19:45.351
Uh. you can't really open both
at the same time.

440
00:19:45.435 --> 00:19:48.438
Okay. I'll just go after you. then.

441
00:20:01.659 --> 00:20:04.203
Look. I just need
to get my lunch money from here.

442
00:20:10.293 --> 00:20:11.502
Okay.

443
00:20:15.214 --> 00:20:16.215
What even are those?

444
00:20:17.634 --> 00:20:19.385
I don't know if it's really your thing.

445
00:20:23.723 --> 00:20:26.059
What's happening with the support staff?

446
00:20:26.142 --> 00:20:27.518
Not getting paid a living wage.

447
00:20:29.687 --> 00:20:31.731
It's been all over the news.

448
00:20:33.358 --> 00:20:37.028
Okay.
The news is a nonfictional TV show

449
00:20:37.111 --> 00:20:40.740
that connects real people to real issues.

450
00:20:40.823 --> 00:20:43.618
-Hmm?
-[scoffs] I know what the news is.

451
00:20:44.702 --> 00:20:46.496
Great. She's all yours.

452
00:20:46.579 --> 00:20:48.748
[gentle music playing]

453
00:20:54.128 --> 00:20:56.214
Thank you.

454
00:20:56.297 --> 00:20:57.757
Mmm.

455
00:21:01.177 --> 00:21:02.470
-Hi. Could you help me with something?
-Come on. man.

456
00:21:02.553 --> 00:21:04.806
Sorry. I'm just trying
to get the lay of the land.

457
00:21:04.889 --> 00:21:07.475
Like. what cliques are where.
who sits with who.

458
00:21:07.558 --> 00:21:09.978
Yeah. I still feel like
you're messing with me.

459
00:21:10.061 --> 00:21:12.313
What's the. uh. agenda here?

460
00:21:12.397 --> 00:21:14.315
[scoffs] I'm not messing with you.

461
00:21:14.399 --> 00:21:16.985
I just have this whole three-point plan.
and the first step is to let--

462
00:21:17.068 --> 00:21:19.153
Band geeks.

463
00:21:19.237 --> 00:21:21.322
Jocks.

464
00:21:21.406 --> 00:21:24.033
D&D nerds.

465
00:21:24.117 --> 00:21:25.493
Stoners.

466
00:21:26.786 --> 00:21:28.538
Kids of parents with Microsoft money.

467
00:21:28.621 --> 00:21:31.124
And kids of parents with Boeing money.

468
00:21:40.591 --> 00:21:42.218
Hi. again. [chuckles]

469
00:21:42.301 --> 00:21:43.511
Which ones are the stoners?

470
00:21:46.472 --> 00:21:47.849
-Crazy.
-No way.

471
00:21:47.932 --> 00:21:49.308
And the Microsoft kids?

472
00:21:51.602 --> 00:21:52.812
-[laughing]
-Seriously?

473
00:21:52.895 --> 00:21:55.481
Hmm.

474
00:21:55.565 --> 00:21:57.650
Could you just point me
in the direction of the senior girls?

475
00:21:57.734 --> 00:21:59.444
And if one of them could have won

476
00:21:59.527 --> 00:22:02.613
Homecoming Queen or one
of the top-tier superlatives. even better.

477
00:22:02.697 --> 00:22:06.325
Oh. okay. So. you're not looking
for just any old person.

478
00:22:06.409 --> 00:22:09.662
You want a cool senior
who can totally boost your popularity?

479
00:22:09.746 --> 00:22:11.789
Yes. exactly.

480
00:22:12.957 --> 00:22:15.126
You should be friends
with that girl over there.

481
00:22:15.209 --> 00:22:17.211
The one with the curly hair.

482
00:22:17.295 --> 00:22:20.298
-Do you want to come with. or--?
-Oh. no. I'm good.

483
00:22:27.513 --> 00:22:28.806
[lively chatter]

484
00:22:28.890 --> 00:22:30.308
Hi. ladies.

485
00:22:30.391 --> 00:22:33.436
I was told this is where
the coolest of the cool seniors sit.

486
00:22:33.519 --> 00:22:37.273
Well. technically. I'm a junior.
but. spiritually. I'm a senior.

487
00:22:37.356 --> 00:22:38.608
[sets tray on table]

488
00:22:38.691 --> 00:22:39.692
Oh. [chuckles]

489
00:22:39.776 --> 00:22:41.277
You're... sitting.

490
00:22:43.488 --> 00:22:45.865
Wait. I thought we were going
to the Bikini Kill show that weekend.

491
00:22:45.948 --> 00:22:47.158
[gasps] So fun.

492
00:22:48.242 --> 00:22:49.869
You know Bikini Kill?

493
00:22:49.952 --> 00:22:51.829
Oh.

494
00:22:51.913 --> 00:22:53.873
I know bikinis.

495
00:22:53.956 --> 00:22:55.416
That kill.

496
00:23:00.213 --> 00:23:03.299
Okay. Whose car are we taking? Or are we
seriously taking a bus to Olympia?

497
00:23:03.382 --> 00:23:04.634
[Katie] What about Miles's?

498
00:23:04.717 --> 00:23:06.219
We can't take a guy's car
to a Bikini Kill show.

499
00:23:06.302 --> 00:23:07.470
I mean. think of how that would look.

500
00:23:07.553 --> 00:23:11.015
Oh. I totally feel your struggle.
All of my friends at home have cars.

501
00:23:11.099 --> 00:23:13.351
It's impossible not to have one
if you live in L.A.

502
00:23:13.434 --> 00:23:17.146
But instead of getting me a car.
my parents moved me to Seattle. Hmm.

503
00:23:17.230 --> 00:23:19.732
L.A.

504
00:23:19.816 --> 00:23:20.942
Yeah. that explains it.

505
00:23:21.025 --> 00:23:22.652
You must be so happy to have escaped.

506
00:23:22.735 --> 00:23:24.153
[chuckling]

507
00:23:24.237 --> 00:23:25.947
What's wrong with L.A.?

508
00:23:26.030 --> 00:23:28.991
Nothing. I-I think
we just value different things here.

509
00:23:29.075 --> 00:23:32.286
like the planet and social justice.

510
00:23:33.371 --> 00:23:37.208
And not being totally entitled and sitting
wherever we want in the cafeteria

511
00:23:37.291 --> 00:23:42.004
on our first day when some of us
have spent four years earning this table.

512
00:23:46.884 --> 00:23:49.053
Have you ever actually been to L.A.?

513
00:23:49.137 --> 00:23:51.722
[laughing]

514
00:23:51.806 --> 00:23:56.853
Uh. no. No. you couldn't pay any of us
to set foot in California.

515
00:23:56.936 --> 00:24:00.565
And this little exchange
is not changing my mind.

516
00:24:00.648 --> 00:24:03.818
Okay. before L.A. Barbie
interrupted us. the jackets.

517
00:24:03.901 --> 00:24:05.027
-Right. the jackets.
-Yeah.

518
00:24:05.111 --> 00:24:07.321
-[Kimberly] You know the ones?
-[laughter]

519
00:24:07.405 --> 00:24:10.533
[indistinct chatter continues]

520
00:24:10.616 --> 00:24:13.452
[upbeat music playing]

521
00:24:17.373 --> 00:24:19.041
Okay. Yeah.

522
00:24:19.125 --> 00:24:22.044
Okay. I'll have him get back to you.

523
00:24:22.128 --> 00:24:23.588
All right. sweetie. Well. good to hear

524
00:24:23.671 --> 00:24:25.381
-she's doing well. Bye.
-Hi.

525
00:24:25.464 --> 00:24:26.966
Hi.

526
00:24:27.550 --> 00:24:29.468
Love the bobbleheads. Très chic.

527
00:24:32.138 --> 00:24:36.475
Could I see the school nurse?
I'm not. um... [clearing throat]

528
00:24:36.559 --> 00:24:38.311
-feeling well.
-Hang on a second. Caleb.

529
00:24:38.394 --> 00:24:40.188
Cafeteria's that way.

530
00:24:40.271 --> 00:24:42.148
Yeah.
I think I'm just gonna skip it today.

531
00:24:42.231 --> 00:24:44.233
Not gonna happen.

532
00:24:44.317 --> 00:24:45.568
Come here.

533
00:24:49.030 --> 00:24:51.115
-I'm serious.
-Thank you. Donna.

534
00:24:55.036 --> 00:24:56.621
Why is he skipping lunch?

535
00:24:58.456 --> 00:24:59.916
His parents haven't paid for school lunch.

536
00:24:59.999 --> 00:25:03.336
but the boy's got to eat.
and I have petty cash. so...

537
00:25:03.419 --> 00:25:05.296
That's so nice.

538
00:25:05.379 --> 00:25:07.298
No one at my old school
would've done that.

539
00:25:08.382 --> 00:25:13.137
Well. the way I see it is that
it is my job to look out for all of you.

540
00:25:13.221 --> 00:25:15.389
And if that means

541
00:25:15.473 --> 00:25:19.602
sneaking into the cafeteria to get someone
a piece of cake for their birthday.

542
00:25:19.685 --> 00:25:24.482
or signing a permission slip
that their parents forgot to sign.

543
00:25:24.565 --> 00:25:27.526
you know.
some rules are made to be broken.

544
00:25:27.610 --> 00:25:29.445
[chuckles]

545
00:25:29.528 --> 00:25:30.780
[gasps]

546
00:25:30.863 --> 00:25:32.490
Is that a Cosmo?

547
00:25:33.574 --> 00:25:34.867
You can tell by the corner?

548
00:25:34.951 --> 00:25:36.202
Of course.

549
00:25:37.161 --> 00:25:41.374
All right.
I know this may not seem like my thing.

550
00:25:41.457 --> 00:25:44.001
but. oh. those little quizzes
are so addictive.

551
00:25:44.085 --> 00:25:45.336
I know!

552
00:25:45.419 --> 00:25:49.382
And their horoscopes have been right
on several occasions.

553
00:25:49.465 --> 00:25:51.425
-It's kind of my bible.
-Oh. my God. Me. too.

554
00:25:51.509 --> 00:25:54.345
I-I just moved here. so I'm waiting for
my subscription to get forwarded here.

555
00:25:54.428 --> 00:25:55.513
Mm.

556
00:25:55.596 --> 00:25:56.555
Could I just...?

557
00:25:59.809 --> 00:26:01.811
[gasps] Thank you.

558
00:26:04.272 --> 00:26:07.191
[sniffs]

559
00:26:07.275 --> 00:26:08.401
[sighs]

560
00:26:08.484 --> 00:26:09.860
Hmm.

561
00:26:10.945 --> 00:26:14.407
Hi. Donna. Um. just give me five.

562
00:26:14.490 --> 00:26:17.535
and then I'm gonna make a few phone calls.

563
00:26:17.618 --> 00:26:18.995
[Donna] Yeah. Absolutely.

564
00:26:19.078 --> 00:26:21.789
Now. there is just one more form
I need you to fill out.

565
00:26:24.166 --> 00:26:27.586
We kind of have a "no chitchat" policy
here in the office.

566
00:26:27.670 --> 00:26:29.130
I totally understand.

567
00:26:29.964 --> 00:26:32.425
Now. I could call your parents

568
00:26:32.508 --> 00:26:35.678
and tell them you have a 24-hour bug
or something.

569
00:26:36.512 --> 00:26:38.389
Or you could spend your lunch in here.

570
00:26:38.472 --> 00:26:40.391
doing that very important paperwork.
of course.

571
00:26:40.474 --> 00:26:43.311
-Mm-hmm.
-And you could give this place a chance.

572
00:26:44.687 --> 00:26:46.230
What kind of chance?

573
00:26:46.314 --> 00:26:49.317
Well. if this was your first day
at your old school.

574
00:26:49.400 --> 00:26:51.193
how would you be spending it?

575
00:26:54.572 --> 00:26:55.740
Hmm.

576
00:26:55.823 --> 00:26:59.160
[gasps] L-E-T-S-G-O.
that's the way we spell "Let's go."

577
00:26:59.243 --> 00:27:01.996
Let's go. Hey. hey. let's go.

578
00:27:02.079 --> 00:27:05.750
And I don't know your mascot.
so go. team. go.

579
00:27:08.252 --> 00:27:10.546
[noisemaker rattling]

580
00:27:10.629 --> 00:27:12.089
Thank you.

581
00:27:12.173 --> 00:27:14.091
I mean. wack.

582
00:27:14.175 --> 00:27:15.301
It's fine. You're in.

583
00:27:15.384 --> 00:27:18.179
Oh. Really?

584
00:27:18.262 --> 00:27:21.682
Don't you need to take a few days
and put up a list or something?

585
00:27:22.475 --> 00:27:24.310
Nah. you're in.

586
00:27:25.394 --> 00:27:27.480
Great. Thank you so much. ladies.

587
00:27:27.563 --> 00:27:29.023
I won't let you down.

588
00:27:29.106 --> 00:27:30.316
Next.

589
00:27:32.485 --> 00:27:35.071
[upbeat music playing]

590
00:27:36.238 --> 00:27:37.573
Good luck.

591
00:27:41.410 --> 00:27:45.289
[slowly] L-E-T-S-G-O.
that's the way we spell "Let's go."

592
00:27:45.373 --> 00:27:48.167
Let's go. Hey. hey. let's go.

593
00:27:48.250 --> 00:27:49.377
Great. you're in.

594
00:27:49.460 --> 00:27:50.878
-Sweet.
-[gasps]

595
00:27:56.092 --> 00:27:57.760
-[grunts]
-[gasps] Oh!

596
00:27:57.843 --> 00:27:59.470
-Oh.
-Oh. [stammers]

597
00:27:59.553 --> 00:28:01.889
-Sorry.
-It's okay. Whew. [chuckles]

598
00:28:01.972 --> 00:28:03.349
Are you okay?

599
00:28:04.934 --> 00:28:08.104
Yeah. I'm great. [chuckles]

600
00:28:08.187 --> 00:28:10.106
-So great.
-Okay.

601
00:28:10.773 --> 00:28:12.191
Okay. [sighs]

602
00:28:16.153 --> 00:28:17.780
[sighs]

603
00:28:21.075 --> 00:28:22.618
Are you sure you're all right?

604
00:28:24.453 --> 00:28:26.080
Does this school not have a football team?

605
00:28:26.163 --> 00:28:30.167
If so. I can't imagine
they're very highly motivated since...

606
00:28:30.251 --> 00:28:32.294
Yeah. football's not really a thing here.

607
00:28:32.378 --> 00:28:33.838
So who do they root for?

608
00:28:34.463 --> 00:28:38.467
I think girls here think
cheering for boys is lame.

609
00:28:38.551 --> 00:28:40.261
[scoffs]

610
00:28:40.344 --> 00:28:44.515
So they just... cheer for themselves?

611
00:28:44.598 --> 00:28:47.852
[gentle music playing]

612
00:28:47.935 --> 00:28:49.353
You got a name?

613
00:28:50.438 --> 00:28:51.480
Elle Woods.

614
00:28:52.440 --> 00:28:53.732
Elle... Woods.

615
00:28:53.816 --> 00:28:54.859
Yeah.

616
00:29:04.535 --> 00:29:05.703
-Okay.
-Ooh.

617
00:29:05.786 --> 00:29:06.829
Mm-hmm.

618
00:29:06.912 --> 00:29:10.082
I have to say. I love my office.

619
00:29:10.166 --> 00:29:11.792
Aw.

620
00:29:11.876 --> 00:29:14.920
-I knew you would.
-Yeah. and the nice thing about

621
00:29:15.004 --> 00:29:18.674
the slower pace is that I-I feel like
I can really spend time with my patients.

622
00:29:18.757 --> 00:29:20.426
like I might actually make a difference.

623
00:29:20.509 --> 00:29:21.552
Me. too.

624
00:29:21.635 --> 00:29:23.471
-[Wyatt] Yeah?
-[Eva] Can you believe

625
00:29:23.554 --> 00:29:25.973
-they didn't have Tae Bo here yet?
-[scoffs]

626
00:29:26.056 --> 00:29:28.309
-Such an interesting place. Eva.
-Yes.

627
00:29:28.976 --> 00:29:30.269
What about you?

628
00:29:30.352 --> 00:29:32.271
-How's the new school?
-Yeah. you said

629
00:29:32.354 --> 00:29:33.772
you tried out for cheer. How was it?

630
00:29:35.149 --> 00:29:37.151
I don't think I'm gonna join.

631
00:29:37.234 --> 00:29:40.571
The girls here just kind of cheer
for themselves.

632
00:29:41.655 --> 00:29:43.199
-I don't get it.
-Hmm.

633
00:29:44.283 --> 00:29:45.951
I think it's feminism.

634
00:29:46.035 --> 00:29:48.621
Yeah. that's very in right now.

635
00:29:48.704 --> 00:29:49.872
[Wyatt] Hmm.

636
00:29:49.955 --> 00:29:52.374
[Eva] It's probably
why Marlena came back to life.

637
00:29:52.458 --> 00:29:54.960
Can you believe
she's not even possessed anymore?

638
00:29:55.044 --> 00:29:56.128
She did?

639
00:29:58.214 --> 00:30:01.133
Honey. Oh. no.
I-I left the tape in your room.

640
00:30:01.217 --> 00:30:02.426
I thought you'd watched it already.

641
00:30:02.510 --> 00:30:04.470
Well. I was saving it
for a pre-dinner treat.

642
00:30:08.974 --> 00:30:10.976
[sighs]
I can't believe we moved here.

643
00:30:11.060 --> 00:30:14.939
[distorted female voice] This will do you
no more good than your bothersome prayers

644
00:30:15.022 --> 00:30:19.109
and your irksome holy water.

645
00:30:19.193 --> 00:30:22.321
-[dramatic TV music playing]
-Oh. all right. all right. all right!

646
00:30:22.404 --> 00:30:24.823
-[sighs]
-I'll play your game.

647
00:30:24.907 --> 00:30:26.951
I've been playing right along.

648
00:30:27.034 --> 00:30:29.411
[sighs] It's not even worth it.

649
00:30:29.495 --> 00:30:32.289
-[Bruiser barks]
-What should be my next move?

650
00:30:37.878 --> 00:30:40.172
Marlena's possession was all I had.

651
00:30:40.256 --> 00:30:41.590
[Bruiser whines]

652
00:30:48.347 --> 00:30:49.390
Hmm.

653
00:30:50.474 --> 00:30:52.059
-[phone rings]
-[gasps]

654
00:30:53.519 --> 00:30:55.771
Elle Woods' residence.
You've reached Elle Woods.

655
00:30:55.854 --> 00:30:57.982
[Madison distorted] Elle!

656
00:30:58.065 --> 00:30:59.650
Madison?

657
00:30:59.733 --> 00:31:01.443
[distorted] Elle. I just got a car phone.

658
00:31:01.527 --> 00:31:02.820
What?

659
00:31:02.903 --> 00:31:05.573
Madison? I can't hear you.

660
00:31:05.656 --> 00:31:07.992
I got a car phone!

661
00:31:08.075 --> 00:31:10.035
Oh! That's so cool.

662
00:31:10.119 --> 00:31:11.620
[chuckles] I know. right?

663
00:31:11.704 --> 00:31:13.956
-Tiffany and Amber are here. too.
-[both] Hi. Elle.

664
00:31:14.039 --> 00:31:15.666
We don't have time for hellos.
Sorry. Elle.

665
00:31:15.749 --> 00:31:17.167
I only have two minutes on this thing

666
00:31:17.251 --> 00:31:19.670
before I start getting charged a gazillion
dollars and my parents kill me.

667
00:31:19.753 --> 00:31:21.338
-[laughs softly]
-But the headline is...

668
00:31:21.422 --> 00:31:23.716
-school was crazy today.
-So crazy.

669
00:31:23.799 --> 00:31:25.009
[laughing]

670
00:31:25.092 --> 00:31:26.552
That-that sounds really fun. you guys.

671
00:31:26.635 --> 00:31:27.803
It was.

672
00:31:27.886 --> 00:31:29.805
-Jeff got a really unfortunate earring.
-Oh.

673
00:31:29.888 --> 00:31:31.056
And Susie got even more

674
00:31:31.140 --> 00:31:33.851
unfortunate highlights. and I think that
Chad and Becca are a thing even though

675
00:31:33.934 --> 00:31:35.102
they're still pretending like they're not.

676
00:31:35.185 --> 00:31:36.854
No. it was literally. like.
a hall of fame first day.

677
00:31:36.937 --> 00:31:39.148
[Tiffany] That's exactly
what I was going to say.

678
00:31:39.231 --> 00:31:40.608
-Hall of fame. Yeah.
-Right?

679
00:31:40.691 --> 00:31:44.028
-Wow.
-[laughing]

680
00:31:44.111 --> 00:31:48.157
Um... has Hot Josh asked

681
00:31:48.240 --> 00:31:49.408
about me?

682
00:31:50.534 --> 00:31:53.120
Not so much in his words.
but in his actions.

683
00:31:53.203 --> 00:31:55.122
-absolutely.
-Mm-hmm.

684
00:31:55.205 --> 00:31:57.207
[Madison] But enough about us.
How was your first day?

685
00:31:57.291 --> 00:31:59.126
Did you make any friends?

686
00:31:59.209 --> 00:32:00.794
Does the school secretary count?

687
00:32:01.879 --> 00:32:04.590
-That's a great jumping-off point.
-Mm-hmm.

688
00:32:05.299 --> 00:32:06.592
I just...

689
00:32:06.675 --> 00:32:09.887
I don't feel like I really speak
the same language as anyone here.

690
00:32:09.970 --> 00:32:11.722
Well. have you tried
learning their language?

691
00:32:11.805 --> 00:32:12.973
What do you mean?

692
00:32:13.057 --> 00:32:14.850
-Get fluent in Seattle.
-Mm.

693
00:32:14.933 --> 00:32:17.353
[laughs] I don't know if that's possible.

694
00:32:17.436 --> 00:32:19.313
-[phone beeps]
-Oh. I'm sorry. Elle. Two minutes are up.

695
00:32:19.396 --> 00:32:20.731
-We-we miss you.
-[both] We love you!

696
00:32:20.814 --> 00:32:22.232
Well. I miss you guys.

697
00:32:22.316 --> 00:32:24.610
[dial tone]

698
00:32:24.693 --> 00:32:25.986
Bye.

699
00:32:31.533 --> 00:32:33.994
Get fluent in Seattle.

700
00:32:34.078 --> 00:32:35.204
[barks]

701
00:32:35.287 --> 00:32:36.372
[gasps]

702
00:32:36.455 --> 00:32:39.375
[♪ INXS sings "New Sensation"]

703
00:32:39.458 --> 00:32:42.086
♪ Live. baby. live ♪

704
00:32:42.878 --> 00:32:45.005
♪ now that the day is over ♪

705
00:32:47.257 --> 00:32:50.678
♪ I got a new sensation ♪

706
00:32:52.054 --> 00:32:55.724
♪ In perfect moments ♪

707
00:32:55.808 --> 00:32:59.728
♪ that's impossible to refuse ♪

708
00:33:02.731 --> 00:33:05.317
♪ Sleep. baby. sleep ♪

709
00:33:05.401 --> 00:33:07.403
♪ now that the night is over ♪

710
00:33:07.486 --> 00:33:08.779
[sighs]

711
00:33:08.862 --> 00:33:10.614
[murmuring]

712
00:33:10.698 --> 00:33:13.033
♪ And the sun comes like a god ♪

713
00:33:13.117 --> 00:33:14.952
Hey.

714
00:33:15.035 --> 00:33:17.079
-♪ into our room ♪
-Hey. girl.

715
00:33:18.831 --> 00:33:23.419
♪ All perfect light and promises ♪

716
00:33:26.004 --> 00:33:27.506
♪ got a hold on you ♪

717
00:33:27.589 --> 00:33:30.551
♪ A new sensation ♪♪

718
00:33:30.634 --> 00:33:31.927
Elle. right?

719
00:33:32.010 --> 00:33:33.387
Yes. Elle Woods.

720
00:33:34.138 --> 00:33:36.557
-And you are Kimberly.
-Mm.

721
00:33:36.640 --> 00:33:38.225
From yesterday.

722
00:33:38.308 --> 00:33:40.644
There's a rumor going around that
I feel like I should make you aware of.

723
00:33:40.728 --> 00:33:42.312
Out of love.

724
00:33:42.396 --> 00:33:43.939
Oh. my God. what is it?

725
00:33:44.022 --> 00:33:47.985
Well. people are saying that you wearing
that shirt is the second worst thing

726
00:33:48.068 --> 00:33:50.612
to ever happen to Nirvana.

727
00:33:50.696 --> 00:33:54.074
Wait. I'm sorry. Did you replace the eyes
with little hearts?

728
00:33:54.825 --> 00:33:57.244
I leaned into its innate smiley-ness.

729
00:33:58.495 --> 00:34:00.330
Did no one ever tell you
that we don't do posers here?

730
00:34:02.040 --> 00:34:03.417
Seattle isn't a costume.

731
00:34:03.500 --> 00:34:06.044
and pink isn't a personality.

732
00:34:06.128 --> 00:34:09.089
[laughter]

733
00:34:11.008 --> 00:34:13.010
[somber music playing]

734
00:34:19.349 --> 00:34:22.102
♪ ♪

735
00:34:22.186 --> 00:34:23.896
[thunder rumbling]

736
00:34:28.776 --> 00:34:30.778
[rain falling]

737
00:34:48.462 --> 00:34:50.714
[sighs]

738
00:34:50.798 --> 00:34:52.508
[squishing]

739
00:34:52.591 --> 00:34:54.259
Mom?

740
00:34:55.719 --> 00:34:57.095
Bruiser?

741
00:34:58.096 --> 00:34:59.807
Anyone?

742
00:35:03.143 --> 00:35:04.853
[sighs]

743
00:35:09.233 --> 00:35:10.234
[beeps]

744
00:35:10.317 --> 00:35:12.236
[autodialing]

745
00:35:13.237 --> 00:35:14.780
[line ringing]

746
00:35:15.614 --> 00:35:18.450
-Hi! You've reached Madison LeDoux's car.
-[sighs]

747
00:35:18.534 --> 00:35:20.118
I've run out of minutes for this month.

748
00:35:20.202 --> 00:35:22.621
but leave a message
and I'll listen to it in 27 days.

749
00:35:22.704 --> 00:35:23.705
[beeps]

750
00:35:24.873 --> 00:35:26.041
[sighs]

751
00:35:35.425 --> 00:35:37.427
[optimistic music playing]

752
00:35:55.946 --> 00:35:57.406
Mom?

753
00:35:57.489 --> 00:35:59.157
In here.

754
00:36:03.453 --> 00:36:04.788
[clears throat]

755
00:36:06.665 --> 00:36:08.417
What is this?

756
00:36:08.500 --> 00:36:12.296
No one could be expected to succeed
in that much gray.

757
00:36:17.342 --> 00:36:18.594
Wait. [grunts]

758
00:36:27.060 --> 00:36:28.562
You hate it?

759
00:36:28.645 --> 00:36:30.105
-No.
-W-- I got

760
00:36:30.188 --> 00:36:32.065
the wrong shade?
You wanted Spring Watermelon?

761
00:36:32.149 --> 00:36:33.275
[sighs]

762
00:36:34.818 --> 00:36:36.570
What?

763
00:36:37.321 --> 00:36:38.739
I love it.

764
00:36:39.698 --> 00:36:41.325
Does your face know you love it?

765
00:36:41.408 --> 00:36:43.076
I do. That's the problem.

766
00:36:43.160 --> 00:36:44.995
I'm-I'm shallow.

767
00:36:45.078 --> 00:36:48.749
What kind of person has
the worst day of her life solved by...

768
00:36:48.832 --> 00:36:50.417
pink drapery?

769
00:36:51.251 --> 00:36:52.628
A nice one.

770
00:36:53.712 --> 00:36:57.549
What if I really am the vapid L.A. girl
they all think I am?

771
00:36:57.633 --> 00:36:59.468
Well. I don't know
if you should be putting so much stock

772
00:36:59.551 --> 00:37:01.637
in the opinions of people
who wear leather jewelry.

773
00:37:01.720 --> 00:37:02.804
You don't understand.

774
00:37:02.888 --> 00:37:04.890
They fight for things like social justice

775
00:37:04.973 --> 00:37:07.267
and hold student auctions

776
00:37:07.351 --> 00:37:09.728
and they write their own... zines.

777
00:37:11.980 --> 00:37:13.148
What's a zine?

778
00:37:13.231 --> 00:37:14.650
Exactly.

779
00:37:16.568 --> 00:37:17.819
You know who you are?

780
00:37:18.820 --> 00:37:20.739
You're a Gemini.

781
00:37:21.782 --> 00:37:23.867
I bet they hate astrology. too. [cries]

782
00:37:23.951 --> 00:37:26.954
That means you are funny

783
00:37:27.037 --> 00:37:29.456
and smart and adaptable.

784
00:37:29.539 --> 00:37:31.917
And you find a way
to make all types of friends.

785
00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:34.252
You say they have depth? They care?

786
00:37:34.336 --> 00:37:36.254
Well. so do you.

787
00:37:36.922 --> 00:37:38.090
[sighs]

788
00:37:38.173 --> 00:37:39.508
You're right.

789
00:37:40.634 --> 00:37:42.177
I do care.

790
00:37:43.470 --> 00:37:45.347
You just have to show them that.

791
00:37:45.847 --> 00:37:48.517
[gentle music playing]

792
00:37:48.600 --> 00:37:50.602
[soft chatter]

793
00:37:53.647 --> 00:37:55.399
-Oh. hi. Donna.
-Hey.

794
00:37:55.482 --> 00:37:58.485
-Have you seen Dustin?
-Uh. yeah. he's right over there.

795
00:37:58.568 --> 00:38:01.154
[Elle] I want to see
if he needs help with his auction.

796
00:38:01.238 --> 00:38:02.572
Does this mean you've made a friend?

797
00:38:02.656 --> 00:38:04.157
Way to fit in.

798
00:38:04.241 --> 00:38:05.575
-Sort of.
-All right.

799
00:38:05.659 --> 00:38:06.952
-Go get 'em. tiger.
-Thanks. Donna.

800
00:38:08.245 --> 00:38:09.663
[Dustin] Okay then.

801
00:38:09.746 --> 00:38:12.416
If. uh. pasta's not your thing.

802
00:38:12.499 --> 00:38:14.167
Yeah. but what about...

803
00:38:14.251 --> 00:38:15.627
[grunts] this basketball?

804
00:38:16.628 --> 00:38:19.131
Is there anything special
about this basketball? It's--

805
00:38:19.214 --> 00:38:20.340
Oh. okay. it's just a basketball.

806
00:38:20.424 --> 00:38:22.467
It's just a basketball. but it...

807
00:38:22.551 --> 00:38:24.553
it's a nice basketball.

808
00:38:26.138 --> 00:38:27.347
[student] This is embarrassing.

809
00:38:27.431 --> 00:38:28.598
[giggling]

810
00:38:28.682 --> 00:38:30.934
I guess I will just keep it for myself.

811
00:38:31.018 --> 00:38:32.686
-All right. what's next?
-[Jacob] Uh.

812
00:38:32.769 --> 00:38:33.979
a-a vase from my mom.

813
00:38:34.062 --> 00:38:37.149
A... vase from Jake's mum.

814
00:38:37.232 --> 00:38:38.567
Any starting bids?

815
00:38:39.317 --> 00:38:41.236
-[chuckling]
-Nah.

816
00:38:42.029 --> 00:38:44.448
I have something I'd like to say.

817
00:38:44.531 --> 00:38:48.243
-[student] This should be good.
-This isn't just any vase.

818
00:38:49.870 --> 00:38:51.913
It is a...

819
00:38:51.997 --> 00:38:54.583
multiuse art piece.

820
00:38:54.666 --> 00:38:56.918
-[light chuckling]
-It can hold flowers.

821
00:38:57.002 --> 00:39:00.213
It can serve as an organizer
for your school supplies.

822
00:39:00.297 --> 00:39:03.133
Or it can just look nice.

823
00:39:03.216 --> 00:39:04.342
[both chuckle]

824
00:39:04.426 --> 00:39:05.802
[quietly] What are you doing?

825
00:39:05.886 --> 00:39:08.305
I am helping the support staff
of this school.

826
00:39:08.388 --> 00:39:10.640
who are being vastly underpaid.

827
00:39:10.724 --> 00:39:12.100
[English accent] Don't you watch the news?

828
00:39:12.684 --> 00:39:14.019
[normal voice] The first rule
of fundraising is

829
00:39:14.102 --> 00:39:15.312
you have to be a salesperson.

830
00:39:15.395 --> 00:39:16.396
Watch.

831
00:39:16.480 --> 00:39:20.275
This vase is also an investment piece.

832
00:39:20.358 --> 00:39:22.152
-Let's say Justin's mom--
-Jacob.

833
00:39:22.235 --> 00:39:26.031
Jacob's mom blows up as an artist
in the next few years.

834
00:39:26.114 --> 00:39:28.658
Do you know how much money
you could make off of this?

835
00:39:28.742 --> 00:39:31.703
Potentially thousands of dollars.

836
00:39:31.787 --> 00:39:33.371
-Mm-hmm. mm-hmm.
-[murmuring]

837
00:39:33.455 --> 00:39:34.915
-[Miles] Twenty bucks.
-[gasping]

838
00:39:34.998 --> 00:39:38.001
[students exclaiming. murmuring]

839
00:39:40.087 --> 00:39:42.214
We have 20 bucks. That's a steal.

840
00:39:42.297 --> 00:39:43.465
[student] Twenty-five.

841
00:39:43.548 --> 00:39:45.258
[gasping. chuckling]

842
00:39:45.342 --> 00:39:47.135
Ooh! Not bad!

843
00:39:47.219 --> 00:39:48.970
But can anyone beat that?

844
00:39:49.054 --> 00:39:50.430
-Thirty.
-[gasping]

845
00:39:50.514 --> 00:39:51.681
[applause]

846
00:39:53.975 --> 00:39:55.393
Going once.

847
00:39:55.477 --> 00:39:56.895
going twice.

848
00:39:56.978 --> 00:39:58.605
Sold to...

849
00:39:58.688 --> 00:39:59.898
Miles.

850
00:40:00.732 --> 00:40:02.317
-Miles.
-[student] Yeah!

851
00:40:02.400 --> 00:40:04.653
[laughing. applause]

852
00:40:05.821 --> 00:40:06.988
I got it.

853
00:40:12.327 --> 00:40:13.328
[Dustin] Okay. what's next?

854
00:40:13.411 --> 00:40:14.538
-Here you go.
-Oh.

855
00:40:14.621 --> 00:40:15.622
It's. uh...

856
00:40:15.705 --> 00:40:16.873
it's really something.

857
00:40:16.957 --> 00:40:17.999
I have to come clean.

858
00:40:18.583 --> 00:40:20.794
Jacob's mom's never going
to make it in the art world.

859
00:40:20.877 --> 00:40:22.587
I am so sorry.

860
00:40:22.671 --> 00:40:24.548
Well. you could've convinced me.

861
00:40:24.631 --> 00:40:26.842
Actually. you did convince me.
That's why I bought it.

862
00:40:26.925 --> 00:40:28.969
-[clears throat] Are we doing this?
-[gasps]

863
00:40:29.052 --> 00:40:30.262
Yes.

864
00:40:30.345 --> 00:40:31.513
Thanks again.

865
00:40:31.596 --> 00:40:32.597
What's next?

866
00:40:35.392 --> 00:40:37.477
Ooh. a jersey.

867
00:40:37.561 --> 00:40:39.396
A Ken Griffey Jr. jersey.

868
00:40:39.479 --> 00:40:41.940
A Ken Griffey Jr. jersey.

869
00:40:42.023 --> 00:40:43.733
[students exclaiming. chuckling]

870
00:40:43.817 --> 00:40:45.652
Let's start the bidding at 20.

871
00:40:48.697 --> 00:40:50.115
How about 15?

872
00:40:54.703 --> 00:40:56.121
Okay. look.

873
00:40:56.621 --> 00:40:58.623
Who cares about Ken Griffey Jr.?

874
00:40:58.707 --> 00:41:00.041
[protesting]

875
00:41:00.125 --> 00:41:04.588
What-what I mean is. we all
obviously care about Ken Griffey Jr.

876
00:41:04.671 --> 00:41:05.881
[agreeing]

877
00:41:05.964 --> 00:41:09.426
But who we care about more
are the people who care about us.

878
00:41:09.509 --> 00:41:11.636
The support staff of the school.

879
00:41:12.429 --> 00:41:13.889
Like Donna.

880
00:41:13.972 --> 00:41:15.265
[agreeing]

881
00:41:15.348 --> 00:41:18.185
Donna's let me eat lunch in her office
every day since I've been here.

882
00:41:18.268 --> 00:41:19.728
even when she wasn't supposed to.

883
00:41:19.811 --> 00:41:21.605
You guys.

884
00:41:21.688 --> 00:41:24.441
she pays for some students' lunches
using petty cash.

885
00:41:25.775 --> 00:41:26.902
Alison.

886
00:41:26.985 --> 00:41:29.196
she's turned a blind eye to your tardies.

887
00:41:29.279 --> 00:41:31.615
She knows it's not your fault
when your mom's been late.

888
00:41:32.824 --> 00:41:35.827
And that's not even mentioning
the permission slips she's signed.

889
00:41:35.911 --> 00:41:37.621
the unexcused absences she doesn't mark.

890
00:41:37.704 --> 00:41:39.748
And I've only been at this school
a couple days.

891
00:41:39.831 --> 00:41:42.626
This is money
going directly into Donna's pocket.

892
00:41:42.709 --> 00:41:46.254
And into the pocket of dozens
of other Donnas at this school.

893
00:41:47.047 --> 00:41:48.632
So I'll ask you again.

894
00:41:48.715 --> 00:41:53.136
Who wants this Ken Griffey Jr. jersey?

895
00:41:53.220 --> 00:41:54.095
Twenty bucks.

896
00:41:54.179 --> 00:41:55.513
-[cheering]
-Yay!

897
00:41:55.597 --> 00:41:56.598
[cheer captain] Thirty.

898
00:41:56.681 --> 00:41:57.807
[gasping. cheering]

899
00:41:59.059 --> 00:42:00.268
-Thirty-five!
-[gasping]

900
00:42:00.352 --> 00:42:01.394
Okay. Alison!

901
00:42:02.562 --> 00:42:04.272
-[quietly] Not bad.
-Yeah. well. looks like

902
00:42:04.356 --> 00:42:05.899
I'm not as shallow as you thought.

903
00:42:05.982 --> 00:42:07.484
I never said you were shallow.

904
00:42:08.568 --> 00:42:09.736
Out loud.

905
00:42:10.570 --> 00:42:11.571
Going once.

906
00:42:13.031 --> 00:42:14.699
Going twice.

907
00:42:16.076 --> 00:42:18.036
Sold to Alison!

908
00:42:18.119 --> 00:42:20.080
-[chuckles]
-[cheering]

909
00:42:20.163 --> 00:42:21.248
[chuckling]

910
00:42:23.124 --> 00:42:25.919
Donna. Donna. Donna.

911
00:42:26.002 --> 00:42:27.837
[students] Donna! Donna!

912
00:42:27.921 --> 00:42:31.633
Donna! Donna! Donna! Donna!

913
00:42:31.716 --> 00:42:34.386
Donna! Donna! Donna!

914
00:42:34.469 --> 00:42:36.179
Donna! Donna!

915
00:42:36.263 --> 00:42:38.807
Donna! Donna! Donna!

916
00:42:38.890 --> 00:42:40.600
Donna! Donna!

917
00:42:40.684 --> 00:42:42.686
-Donna!
-[indistinct chatter]

918
00:42:50.193 --> 00:42:51.778
Oh. Donna!

919
00:42:51.861 --> 00:42:53.113
-Take care. girls.
-Bye. Donna.

920
00:42:54.531 --> 00:42:55.573
[stammers]

921
00:43:01.204 --> 00:43:02.205
[door closes]

922
00:43:02.289 --> 00:43:03.707
Hey. 90210.

923
00:43:03.790 --> 00:43:05.250
Get anyone fired lately?

924
00:43:05.333 --> 00:43:06.835
What?

925
00:43:06.918 --> 00:43:08.295
Oh. you didn't hear?

926
00:43:08.378 --> 00:43:10.672
Your little stunt yesterday
got Donna fired.

927
00:43:12.215 --> 00:43:13.300
Turns out. when you announce

928
00:43:13.383 --> 00:43:16.720
every single rule someone's broken
to the entire school.

929
00:43:16.803 --> 00:43:18.680
they get punished for it.

930
00:43:18.763 --> 00:43:19.764
Who knew?

931
00:43:19.848 --> 00:43:22.309
Oh. well. maybe except everyone.

932
00:43:22.392 --> 00:43:23.727
[stammers] That's n...

933
00:43:23.810 --> 00:43:25.812
[sighs]
I was just trying to help.

934
00:43:25.895 --> 00:43:26.896
Oh. yeah?

935
00:43:26.980 --> 00:43:28.273
How'd that go?

936
00:43:28.356 --> 00:43:30.150
[♪ Radiohead plays "Creep"]

937
00:43:32.152 --> 00:43:34.654
♪ But I'm a creep ♪

938
00:43:37.615 --> 00:43:41.161
♪ I'm a weirdo ♪

939
00:43:42.162 --> 00:43:45.582
♪ What the hell am I doing here? ♪♪

940
00:43:48.418 --> 00:43:50.670
[sighs] Okay. I can do this.

941
00:43:50.754 --> 00:43:52.589
[upbeat music playing]

942
00:43:52.672 --> 00:43:54.257
Everything just feels backwards here.

943
00:43:54.341 --> 00:43:55.925
This doesn't seem sanitary.

944
00:43:56.009 --> 00:43:57.344
Happy Monday. Pink Slip.

945
00:43:57.427 --> 00:43:58.762
Oh. this isn't a slip.

946
00:43:58.845 --> 00:44:01.389
It's more of an alpaca tweed.

947
00:44:01.473 --> 00:44:02.390
I assume you're mad at me. too.

948
00:44:02.474 --> 00:44:04.017
I actually didn't even notice you.

949
00:44:04.100 --> 00:44:05.560
Which. I don't know. is that worse?

950
00:44:05.643 --> 00:44:06.811
[groaning]

951
00:44:06.895 --> 00:44:08.563
[Eva] High school is hard for everyone.

952
00:44:08.646 --> 00:44:09.773
no matter where you live.

953
00:44:09.856 --> 00:44:11.858
[Elle] Kimberly's obviously relishing

954
00:44:11.941 --> 00:44:12.817
my fall from grace.

955
00:44:12.901 --> 00:44:16.237
I think you're overestimating
how much people liked you before this.

956
00:44:16.321 --> 00:44:18.323
[Eva] But you are going to win over

957
00:44:18.406 --> 00:44:20.909
this entire city before you know it.

958
00:44:20.992 --> 00:44:22.494
[high-pitched ringing]

959
00:44:22.577 --> 00:44:24.079
[cheering]

960
00:44:24.162 --> 00:44:25.372
-You could be concussed.
-I'm fine.

961
00:44:25.455 --> 00:44:27.582
On the drive over here. you claimed
your favorite color was charcoal.

962
00:44:28.541 --> 00:44:29.542
I did not say that.

963
00:44:29.626 --> 00:44:31.753
Just testing your short-term memory.
You passed.

964
00:44:31.836 --> 00:44:33.463
[Elle] I kind of like someone here

965
00:44:33.546 --> 00:44:35.340
who I really can't like.

966
00:44:35.423 --> 00:44:36.758
Is it unrequited?

967
00:44:36.841 --> 00:44:37.842
[scoffs]

968
00:44:37.926 --> 00:44:39.344
How could it be unrequited?
You're Elle Woods.

969
00:44:39.427 --> 00:44:41.096
I'm sorry I said that.

970
00:44:41.179 --> 00:44:42.806
[lively music playing]

971
00:44:42.889 --> 00:44:44.265
[Donna] I don't know
why you won't give that girl

972
00:44:44.349 --> 00:44:45.517
a chance.

973
00:44:45.600 --> 00:44:47.310
[Elle] And maybe there are
other sides to me.

974
00:44:47.394 --> 00:44:48.645
Maybe I'm not the rule-abiding

975
00:44:48.728 --> 00:44:49.896
Gemini I always thought.

976
00:44:49.979 --> 00:44:52.315
When did detention get so uncool?

977
00:44:53.483 --> 00:44:54.442
I have this petition.

978
00:44:54.526 --> 00:44:55.860
It's for the greater good.

979
00:44:56.361 --> 00:44:57.487
Why won't you fight this with me?

980
00:44:57.570 --> 00:44:59.656
Because neither of us have a law degree.

981
00:44:59.739 --> 00:45:01.491
[Elle] I have a Jackie O suit skirt

982
00:45:01.574 --> 00:45:02.784
I have been dying to mobilize.

983
00:45:02.867 --> 00:45:03.910
[Eva] God. I miss L.A.

984
00:45:03.993 --> 00:45:05.662
At least there we could keep Elle safe

985
00:45:05.745 --> 00:45:07.038
from the criminal element.

986
00:45:07.122 --> 00:45:08.998
She trick-or-treated
at the Menendez house.

987
00:45:09.082 --> 00:45:09.958
[cheering]

988
00:45:10.041 --> 00:45:11.709
[Madison] I feel like
I don't even know you.

989
00:45:11.793 --> 00:45:13.962
When you're ready to be Elle Woods again.
give me a call.

990
00:45:14.045 --> 00:45:15.296
[gasps]

991
00:45:15.380 --> 00:45:17.507
I think you got to ask yourself
who you'd rather disappoint.

992
00:45:17.590 --> 00:45:19.342
your mom or yourself.

993
00:45:19.426 --> 00:45:20.718
[Anderson] Officer. can we arrest her?

994
00:45:20.802 --> 00:45:22.220
Absolutely not.

995
00:45:22.303 --> 00:45:23.304
She's in Chanel.

996
00:45:23.388 --> 00:45:25.807
-[cheering]
-E-L-L-E!

997
00:45:25.890 --> 00:45:27.892
-That's how we spell "victory"!
-[barks]

998
00:45:28.601 --> 00:45:29.853
Yes.

999
00:45:29.936 --> 00:45:31.855
♪ ♪

1000
00:45:35.024 --> 00:45:36.484
-[♪ Radiohead plays "Creep"]
-♪ But I'm a creep ♪

1001
00:45:40.530 --> 00:45:44.492
♪ I'm a weirdo ♪

1002
00:45:45.535 --> 00:45:49.247
♪ What the hell am I doing here? ♪

1003
00:45:51.040 --> 00:45:54.002
♪ I don't belong here ♪

1004
00:45:54.836 --> 00:45:56.963
♪ Oh. oh ♪

1005
00:45:57.046 --> 00:46:01.968
♪ She's running out ♪

1006
00:46:02.051 --> 00:46:06.014
♪ the door ♪

1007
00:46:08.057 --> 00:46:12.979
♪ She's running out ♪

1008
00:46:13.062 --> 00:46:16.983
♪ She run. run. run ♪

1009
00:46:17.066 --> 00:46:23.990
♪ run... ♪♪

1009
00:46:24.305 --> 00:47:24.603
